sols_latex:
The first plane

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}y-z=1
\end{align*}

has normal \textbf{n$_1$}={[}0,1,-1{]} (just the coefficients on x,y,z).
The second plane

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}2x+y+z=2
\end{align*}

has normal \textbf{n$_2$}={[}2,1,1{]}. Let's call the direction our line
has \textbf{v}. Notice that since \textbf{v} is an intersection of the
two planes then by definition it is on plane 1 and plane 2. Therefore

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{n}_1\times\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{0} \quad\text{and}\quad \mathbf{n}_2\times\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{0}.
\end{align*}

Therefore we seek \textbf{v} so that it is orthogonal to both normal
vectors. The cross product, by definition, provides this direction.
Therefore,

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{n}_1\times\mathbf{n}_2=[0,1,-1]\times[2,1,1]=[2,-2,-2].
\end{align*}

We want this to have length 1 and so we see that

\begin{align*}
|\mathbf{v}|=\sqrt{12}=2\sqrt{3}.
\end{align*} Therefore we get that the unit
norm vector, $\mathbf{\hat{v}}$ is

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{\hat{v}}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}[1,-1,-1].
\end{align*}

Since a vector on the line has to be on each plane, it has to be a
solution of a linear system. We have the following equations

\begin{align*}
\left\{
\begin{aligned}
y-z&=1\\
2x+y+z&=2
\end{aligned}\right.
\end{align*}

which is a linear system with 2 equations in 3 unknowns. We can write it
in an augmented matrix as

\begin{align*}
\left[\begin{array}{ccc|c}
0  &  1  &  -1  &  1\\
2  &  1  &  1  &  2
\end{array}\right]
\end{align*}

We will swap the first two rows and then row reduce to get

\begin{align*}
\left[\begin{array}{ccc|c}
1  &  0  &  1  &  1/2\\
0  &  1  &  -1  &  1
\end{array}\right].
\end{align*}

We notice there is a free variable and we let \emph{x} = \emph{t}. We
then get

\begin{align*}
z&=\frac{1}{2}-t\\
y&=1+z=\frac{3}{2}-t
\end{align*}

Therefore we get that the solution, \textbf{s}, is

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{s}=\mathbf{s}_0+t\mathbf{v}=\left[0,\frac{3}{2},\frac{1}{2}\right]+t[1,-1,-1].
\end{align*}

The direction part of the line, \textbf{v} is {[}1,-1,-1{]}. However to
make it length 1 we must divide by its magnitude,
$|\mathbf{v}|=\sqrt{3}$ to get,

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{\hat{v}}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}[1,-1,-1]
\end{align*}

just like in
{solution
1}.

statement_latex:
